wing'\n| chapter 5 of Sinclair collection\n|-\n\n| 188?\n| \"Mysteries\"\n| \n| \"Mysteries\"\n| (chapter 8 in Sinclair) on Greek religion\n|-\n\n| 1887\n| \"La Philosophie de Pascale\"\n| La Revue des deux mondes 80 (1887) 399\u2013428\n| \"Pascal\u2019s Philosophy\"\n| translated by Mark Sinclair in Ravaisson, Selected Essays, 253\u201378\n|-\n\n| 1892\n| \"Venus de Milo\"\n| second extended version of Venus essay\n| \"Venus de Milo\"\n| the philosophical 3rd section in Chapter 6 of Sinclair book\n|-\n\n| 1893\n| \"M\u00e9taphysique et morale\"\n| Revue de m\u00e9taphysique et morale 1, 1893, 6\u201325\n| \"Metaphysics and Morals\"\n| translated by Mark Sinclair in Ravaisson, Selected Essays, 279\u201394.\n|-\n\n| 1901\n| \"Testament philosophique\"\n| first edited and published by Xavier L\u00e9on in Revue de m\u00e9taphysique et de morale 9/1 (1901) 1\u201331 from notes left after his death\n| \n| \n|-\n\n| 1933\n| ''Testament philosophique''\n| expanded version by Charles Devivaise \n| ''Philosophical Testament''\n| translated by J. Dunham and M. Sinclair in Ravaisson, Selected Essays, 295\u2013336\n|-\n\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:10pt;\"| Notes<br />\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* '''a''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_a}} Sinclair in ''Being Inclined'': 'In 1834' when 21 years of age, Ravaisson 'was the remarkably young laureate of a competition organized by the ''Acad\u00e9mie des sciences morales et politiques'' on Aristotle\u2019s ''Metaphysics'' and its historical reception, with a dissertation - ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' - that he would later publish in a revised and expanded form as ''Essai sur la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' [Volume 1] (1837).<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref> See also Sinclair 'Introduction' in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-2-3\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 2-3</ref>\n* '''b''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_a}} Sinclair in ''Being Inclined'': 'Long sections of' ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' 'with the original pagination in the margins, are published in R. Belay and C. Marin, ''De la nature \u00e0 l\u2019esprit'' (Paris: ENS Editions, 2001), 201\u201313.'<ref name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''c''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_c}} Revised and expanded version of Ravaisson's 1834 prize winning essay ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref>\n* '''d''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_d}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-6\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 6</ref>\n* '''e''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_e}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''f''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_f}} See Sinclair's ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref>\n* '''g''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_g}} As well as translating the text, Carlisle and Sinclair also include an two extensive supplements by way of an \"Editors\u2019 Introduction\" and \"Editors\u2019 Commentary\".<ref name=\"Carlisle&Sinclair-1-21&78-114\">\"Carlisle & Sinclair (2008), pp. 1-21; 78-114</ref> In addition, there is a long preface from Catherine Malabou titled \"Addiction and Grace\".\n* '''h''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_h}} This publication is a bilingual edition of the text and presents both ''De l\u2019habitude'' and the translation by Carlisle and Sinclair (''Of Habit'') on facing pages of the book. The French version is the Alcan edition of 1933.<ref name=\"Carlisle&Sinclair-20\">\"Carlisle & Sinclair (2008), p. 20</ref>\n* '''i''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_i}} Sinclair writes that the translation has been modified since the original translation by Carlisle and himself a few years earlier in F\u00e9lix Ravaisson ''Of Habit'' (London/New York: Continuum, 2008).<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\" />\n* '''j''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_j}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-6\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 6</ref>\n* '''k''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_k}} Translation by Alain Petit, preceded by an introduction from Petit titled \"Le sympt\u00f4me Speusippe: le spectre de l\u2019\u00e9manatisme dans la pens\u00e9e m\u00e9taphysique de Ravaisson\" (2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cairn.info/revue-cahiers-philosophiques1-2012-2-page-68.htm#|title=Ravaisson, la doctrine de Speusippe sur les premiers principes selon le t\u00e9moignage d'Aristote|publisher=Cahiers Philosophiques|date=2012|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* '''l''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_l}} See also Sinclair's commentary in 'Introduction' in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-8-9\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 8-9</ref>\n* '''m''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_m}} See Sinclair's commentary in 'Introduction' in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-3-4\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 3-4</ref> Sinclair points out that this second volume developed (but did not repeat) work from his 1834 prize winning essay ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' (1834) which had been revised and expanded in volume one (1837). Sinclair also mentions that a third and fourth volume were planned, but never came to fruition. In a footnote, however, Sinclair continues that Charles Devivaise 'published some of Ravaisson's work towards the third volume as ''Essai sur la Metaphysique d'Aristote: Fragments du Tome III'' (Paris: Vrin, 1953)'.<ref name=\"SinclairI-25\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 25</ref> \n|}\n\n==References==\n'''General: Primary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Sinclair, Mark'''. ''Being Inclined: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson\u2019s Philosophy of Habit'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2019)\n{{refend}}\n\n\n'''General: Secondary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Carlisle, Clare'''. \"Between Freedom and Necessity: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson on Habit and the Moral Life\", in ''Inquiry'' (43/2: 2010), pp. 123\u201345\n*'''Carlisle, Clare and Mark Sinclair'''. \"Editors\u2019 Introduction\" and \"Editors\u2019 Commentary\" in F\u00e9lix Ravaisson ''Of Habit'', translation, introduction, and com