0}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Pathardi tehsil topics}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Pathardi taluka]]\n[[Category:Villages in Ahmednagar district]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "/* References *", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ambika_nagar"}
{"title_page": "Hildelith Cumming", "text_new": "[[File:Hildelith_Cumming.jpg|thumb|right|Hildelith Cumming in 1976.]]\nDame '''Hildelith Cumming''' (1909 \u2013 1991), born '''Barbara Theresa Cumming''', was a British nun, printer and musician. Cumming converted to [[Roman Catholic]]ism about the age of 30, joining [[Stanbrook Abbey]], Worcestershire. There she took over management of the printing press for many years. \n\n==Biography==\nCumming was born in [[Battersea]] on 15 December 1909. Her father, Frederick Mann Cumming, was a civil engineer's assistant and her mother was Emma Georgina Love. She attended school in [[Clapham]], before studying at the [[Royal Academy of Music]]. There she also gained teaching qualifications and was appointed a piano sub-professor in 1932, however, she moved on within a year to Wentworth's [[Bournemouth Collegiate School|Collegiate School for Girls]]<ref name=ODNB>{{cite ODNB|id=49617|title=Cumming, Barbara Theresa [name in religion Hildelith Cumming]}}</ref>\n\nAround 1930, Cumming joined [[Oxford Group]], falling in love with one of the members, but was not given permission to marry by the groups leader. In 1940, the Collegiate School was evacuated to [[Llangollen]], where she converted to [[Roman Catholic]]ism. On 18 December 1941, she took her vows as a [[Benedictine]] nun at [[Stanbrook Abbey]], [[Worcestershire]]. She took the name Hildelith and would remain attached to the abbey for the remainder of her life. Cumming took on a number of musical roles within the abbey, including assistant organist, director of choir and director of music.<ref name=ODNB /><ref name=Obit/> While at the abbey, she was bestowed the Benedictine honorific title of \"Dame\".<ref name=:100/>\n\nCumming took over management of the [[Stanbrook Abbey Press]] in 1952, after the press was recommended for closure.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yorkshire Post: Religious order contemplates Yorkshire move |work=Yorkshire Post |date=5 April 2005}}</ref> She was taught the art of printing by [[John Dreyfus]] and [[Jan van Krimpen]] and became renowned for her book designs and printing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuns' secret trip to polling booth |work=Daily Telegraph |date=6 December 2005 |location=London, England}}</ref><ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite news |title=Sister Hildelith Cumming - Obituary |work=The Times |date=8 May 1991 |location=London, England}}</ref> In 1976, the press celebrated its centenary, being referred to as one of the oldest functioning private printing press in the country.<ref name=:100>{{cite news |last1=Gosling |first1=Kenneth |title=Nuns' press celebrates 100 years |work=The Times |issue=59858 |date=11 November 1976 |location=London, England |page=5}}</ref>\n\nShe retired from printing projects in 1982, after suffering a heart attack and deteriorating health. Cumming died on 19 April 1991.<ref name=ODNB />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cumming, Hildelith}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Benedictine nuns]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:British printers]]\n[[Category:People from Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian nuns]]\n[[Category:Private press movement people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Hildelith_Cumming.jpg|thumb|right|Hildelith Cumming in 1976.]]\nDame '''Hildelith Cumming''' (1909 \u2013 1991), born '''Barbara Theresa Cumming''', was a British nun, printer and musician. Cumming converted to [[Roman Catholic]]ism about the age of 30, joining [[Stanbrook Abbey]], Worcestershire. There she took over management of the printing press for many years. \n\n==Biography==\nCumming was born in [[Battersea]] on 15 December 1909. Her father, Frederick Mann Cumming, was a civil engineer's assistant and her mother was Emma Georgina Love. She attended school in [[Clapham]], before studying at the [[Royal Academy of Music]]. There she also gained teaching qualifications and was appointed a piano sub-professor in 1932, however, she moved on within a year to [[Wentworth]]'s [[Bournemouth Collegiate School|Collegiate School for Girls]]<ref name=ODNB>{{cite ODNB|id=49617|title=Cumming, Barbara Theresa [name in religion Hildelith Cumming]}}</ref>\n\nAround 1930, Cumming joined [[Oxford Group]], falling in love with one of the members, but was not given permission to marry by the groups leader. In 1940, the Collegiate School was evacuated to [[Llangollen]], where she converted to [[Roman Catholic]]ism. On 18 December 1941, she took her vows as a [[Benedictine]] nun at [[Stanbrook Abbey]], [[Worcestershire]]. She took the name Hildelith and would remain attached to the abbey for the remainder of her life. Cumming took on a number of musical roles within the abbey, including assistant organist, director of choir and director of music.<ref name=ODNB /><ref name=Obit/> While at the abbey, she was bestowed the Benedictine honorific title of \"Dame\".<ref name=:100/>\n\nCumming took over management of the [[Stanbrook Abbey Press]] in 1952, after the press was recommended for closure.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yorkshire Post: Religious order contemplates Yorkshire move |work=Yorkshire Post |date=5 April 2005}}</ref> She was taught the art of printing by [[John Dreyfus]] and [[Jan van Krimpen]] and became renowned for her book designs and printing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuns' secret trip to polling booth |work=Daily Telegraph |date=6 December 2005 |location=London, England}}</ref><ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite news |title=Sister Hildelith Cumming - Obituary |work=The Times |date=8 May 1991 |location=London, England}}</ref> In 1976, the press celebrated its centenary, being referred to as one of the oldest functioning private printing press in the country.<ref name=:100>{{cite news |last1=Gosling |first1=Kenneth |title=Nuns' press celebrates 100 years |work=The Times |issue=59858 |date=11 November 1976 |location=London, England |page=5}}</ref>\n\nShe retired from printing projects in 1982, after suffering a heart attack and deteriorating health. Cumming died on 19 April 1991.<ref name=ODNB />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cumming, Hildelith}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Benedictine nuns]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:British printers]]\n[[Category:People from Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian nuns]]\n[[Category:Private press movement people]]\n", "name_user": "Worm That Turned", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unlinked:Wentworth", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hildelith_Cumming"}
{"title_page": "William James Sidis", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|American child prodigy}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jenik patel\n| other_names        = {{unordered list|John W. Shattuck|Frank Folupa|Parker Greene|Jacob Marmor}}\n| image              = William James Sidis 1914.jpg\n| caption            = William James Sidis at his [[Harvard University|Harvard]] graduation (1914)\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1898|4|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manhattan, New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1944|7|17|1898|4|1}}\n| death_place        = [[South Boston]], [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States\n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[Rice University]]\n| notable_works      = {{unordered list|''[[The Animate and the Inanimate]]'' (1925)|''[[The Tribes and the States]]'' ({{circa|1935|lk=no}})}}\n}}\n\n'''William James Sidis''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|a\u026a|d|\u026a|s}}; April 1, 1898 \u2013 July 17, 1944) was an American [[child prodigy]] with exceptional mathematical and linguistic skills. He is notable for his 1920 book ''[[The Animate and the Inanimate]]'', in which he postulates the existence of [[dark matter]], [[entropy]], and the origin of life in the context of [[thermodynamics]]. Sidis was raised in a particular manner by his father, psychologist [[Boris Sidis]], who wished his son to be gifted. Sidis first became famous for his precocity and later for his [[Eccentricity (behavior)|eccentricity]] and withdrawal from public life. Eventually, he avoided mathematics altogether, writing on other subjects under a number of [[pseudonym]]s. He entered [[Harvard University|Harvard]] at age 11 and, as an adult, was claimed to have an extremely high IQ, and to be conversant in about 25 languages and dialects. Some of these claims have not been verified, but many of his contemporaries, including [[Norbert Wiener]], [[Daniel Frost Comstock]] and [[William James]], supported the assertion that he was extremely intelligent.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Parents and upbringing (1898\u20131908)===\nWilliam James Sidis was born to Jewish emigrants from Ukraine,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayifoundout.com/index.php/2013/12/genius-among-us-sad-story-william-j-sidis/|title=A Genius Among Us: The Sad Story of William J. Sidis|date=December 6, 2013|newspaper=Today I Found Out|language=en-US|access-date=December 9, 2016}}</ref> on April 1, 1898, in [[New York City]]. His father, [[Boris Sidis]], PhD, M.D., had emigrated in 1887 to escape political persecution.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|2\u20134}} His mother, Sarah (Mandelbaum) Sidis, M.D., and her family had fled the [[pogrom]]s in the late 1880s.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|7}} Sarah attended [[Boston University]] and graduated from its [[Boston University School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoint.org/history/king/3-05.htm |title=History of Homeopathy and Its Institutions in America By William Harvey King, M.D., LL.D. Presented by Sylvain Cazalet |publisher=Homeoint.org |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWilliam was named after his godfather, Boris' friend and colleague, the American philosopher [[William James]]. Boris was a [[psychiatrist]] and published numerous books and articles, performing pioneering work in [[psychopathology|abnormal psychology]]. He was a [[polyglot]], and his son William would become one at a young age.\n\nSidis's parents believed in nurturing a [[wiktionary:precocious|precocious]] and fearless love of knowledge (but their methods of parenting were criticized in the media and retrospectively<ref name=\"nyt1909\"/><ref name= Wallace />{{rp|281, Epilogue}}). Sidis could read ''[[The New York Times]]'' at 18 months.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|23}} By age eight, he had reportedly taught himself eight languages ([[Latin]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[French language|French]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[German language|German]], [[Hebrew]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and [[Armenian language|Armenian]]) and invented another, which he called \"Vendergood\".\n\n===Harvard University and college life (1909\u20131915)===\nAlthough the University had previously refused to let his father enroll him at age 9 because he was still a child, Sidis set a record in 1909 by becoming the youngest person to enroll at [[Harvard University]]. In early 1910, Sidis' mastery of higher mathematics was such that he lectured the Harvard Mathematical Club on [[Four-dimensional space|four-dimensional bodies]] which brought him nationwide attention.<ref>{{cite journal| url= https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1977-31409-001| via= APA.org| title= William James Sidis, the broken twig| last= Montour| first= Kathleen| work= [[American Psychologist]]| volume= 32| number= 4| pages= 265\u2013279| doi= 10.1037/0003-066X.32.4.265| date= April 1977| access-date= February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Wonderful Boys of History Compared With Sidis. All Except Macaulay Showed Special Ability in Mathematics. Instances of Boys Having 'Universal Genius' |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E0CE2DC1139E333A25755C1A9679C946196D6CF |date=January 16, 1910| page= SM11| work=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate= November 26, 2014}}</ref> Notable child prodigy, [[cybernetics]] pioneer [[Norbert Wiener]], who also attended Harvard at the time and knew Sidis later stated in his book ''Ex-Prodigy'': \"The talk would have done credit to a first or second-year graduate student of any age...talk represented the triumph of the unaided efforts of a very brilliant child.\"<ref>{{cite web| title= A Review of Kathleen Montour's William James Sidis, The Broken Twig | first= Doug| last= Renselle| website= Quantonics.com| publisher= | url= http://www.quantonics.com/Review_of_WJS_The_Broken_Twig.html| access-date= February 13, 2020}}</ref> MIT Physics professor [[Daniel F. Comstock]] was full of praises: \"[[Karl Friedrich Gauss]] is the only example in history, of all prodigies, whom Sidis resembles. I predict that young Sidis will be a great astronomical mathematician. He will evolve new theories and invent new ways of calculating astronomical phenomena. I believe he will be a great mathematician, the leader in that science in the future.\"<ref name= Wallace>{{cite book | last = Wallace | first = Amy  | title = The prodigy: a biography of William James Sidis, the world's greatest child prodigy | publisher = Macmillan | location = London | date = 1986 | isbn = 9780333432235}}</ref> Sidis began taking a full-time course load in 1910 and earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree, ''[[cum laude]]'', on June 18, 1914, at age 16.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.sidis.net/transcript1.jpg|title=Harvard College, 1952 |via= Sidis.net |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nShortly after graduation, he told reporters that he wanted to live the perfect life, which to him meant living in seclusion. He granted an interview to a reporter from the ''[[Boston Herald]]''. The paper reported Sidis's vows to remain [[Celibacy|celibate]] and never to marry, as he said women did not appeal to him. Later he developed a strong affection for a young woman named [[Martha Foley]]. He later enrolled at [[Harvard Graduate School of Arts and Sciences]].\n\nAccording to ''The Prodigy: a Biography of William James Sidis'', he briefly served at the [[League of Nations]] before leaving because U.S. president [[Woodrow Wilson]] would not withdraw troops deployed during [[World War I|the Great War]]. He was outspoken about his [[pacifism]].\n\n===Teaching and further education (1915\u20131919)===\nAfter a group of Harvard students threatened Sidis physically, his parents secured him a job at the [[William Marsh Rice]] Institute for the Advancement of Letters, Science, and Art (now [[Rice University]]) in [[Houston, Texas]], as a mathematics teaching assistant. He arrived at Rice in December 1915 at the age of 17. He was a graduate fellow working toward his doctorate.\n\nSidis taught three classes: [[Euclidean geometry]], [[non-Euclidean geometry]], and freshman math (he wrote a textbook for the Euclidean geometry course in Greek).<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|112}} After less than a year, frustrated with the department, his teaching requirements, and his treatment by students older than himself, Sidis left his post and returned to New England. When a friend later asked him why he had left, he replied, \"I never knew why they gave me the job in the first place\u2014I'm not much of a teacher. I didn't leave: I was asked to go.\" Sidis abandoned his pursuit of a graduate degree in mathematics and enrolled at the [[Harvard Law School]] in September 1916, but withdrew in good standing in his final year in March 1919.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/transcripts.htm |title=Harvard Transcripts |via= Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Politics and arrest (1919\u20131921)===\nIn 1919, shortly after his withdrawal from law school, Sidis was arrested for participating in a socialist [[May Day]] parade in Boston that turned violent. He was sentenced to 18 months in prison under the [[Sedition Act of 1918]] by Roxbury Municipal Court Judge [[Albert F Hayden]]. Sidis' arrest featured prominently in newspapers, as his early graduation from Harvard had garnered considerable local celebrity status. During the trial, Sidis stated that he had been a [[conscientious objector]] to the [[World War I]] draft, was a [[socialism|socialist]], and did not believe in a god like the \"big boss of the Christians,\" but rather in something that is in a way apart from a human being.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sidis Gets Year and Half in Jail|url=http://www.sidis.net/herald1919.htm |accessdate= January 12, 2018 |work= [[Boston Herald]] |date=May 14, 1919|quote='Do you believe in a god?' 'No.' Atty. Connolly then asked the court what God he meant, whereupon Judge Hayden replied, God Almighty. Here Sidis said that the kind of a God that he did not believe in was the 'big boss of the Christians,' adding that he believed in something that is in a way apart from a human being.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mahony |first1=Dan |title=Frequently Asked Questions About W. J. Sidis |url= http://www.sidis.net/sidisfaq.htm |accessdate=January 12, 2018|quote=\"Was he religious? 'He espoused no religion, but said that... the kind of a God he did not believe in was the \"big boss of the Christians\", adding that he believed in something that is in a way apart from a human being (Boston Herald, May 14, 1919).'\"}}</ref> He later developed his own [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] philosophy based on individual rights and \"the American social continuity\".<ref name = Libertarian>{{Cite journal| last = Sidis | first = William James | title = Libertarian | journal = Continuity News | issue = 2 | page = 4 |date = June 1938| location = Cambridge, Massachusetts| url = http://www.sidis.net/libertarian.htm }}</ref><ref name =\"TheConceptof 'Rights'\">{{Cite journal | last = Sidis | first = William James | title = The Concept of Rights | publisher = American Independence Society | url = http://www.sidis.net/rights2.htm |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> His father arranged with the district attorney to keep Sidis out of prison before his appeal came to trial; his parents, instead, held him in their sanatorium in New Hampshire for a year. They took him to [[California]], where he spent another year.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/railroading.htm |title=Railroading in the Past |via= Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> While at the sanatorium, his parents set about \"reforming\" him and threatened him with transfer to an insane asylum.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n===Later life (1921\u20131944)===\nAfter returning to the East Coast in 1921, Sidis was determined to live an independent and private life. He only took work running adding machines or other fairly menial tasks. He worked in New York City and became estranged from his parents. It took years before he was cleared legally to return to Massachusetts, and he was concerned about his risk of arrest for years. He obsessively collected streetcar [[Transfer (public transit)|transfers]], wrote self-published periodicals, and taught small circles of interested friends his version of American history. In 1933, Sidis passed a Civil Service exam in New York, but scored a low ranking of 254.<ref name=ioipj /> In a private letter, Sidis wrote that this was \"not so encouraging\".<ref name=ioipj /> In 1935, he wrote an unpublished manuscript, ''[http://www.mortenbrask.com/wp-content/uploads/The-tribes-and-the-states-SIDIS.pdf The Tribes and the States]'', which traces [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] contributions to [[American democracy]].<ref>{{cite journal| title= William James Sidis' 'Tribes and States': An Unpublished Exploration of Native American Contributions to Democracy| last= Johansen| first= Bruce E.| work= [[Northeast Indian Quarterly]]| volume= 6 |number= 3| pages= 24\u201329 |date= Fall 1989| url= https://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ404329| via= eric.ed.gov| access-date= }}</ref>\n\nIn 1944, Sidis won a settlement from ''[[The New Yorker]]'' for an article published in 1937.<ref>{{Cite journal |last= Bates |first=Stephen |year=2011 |title=The Prodigy and the Press: William James Sidis, Anti-Intellectualism, and Standards of Success |journal=[[Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly|J&MC Quarterly]] |issn=1077-6990 |volume=88 |issue=2 |pages=374\u2013397 |doi=10.1177/107769901108800209 |ref=harv }}</ref> He had alleged it contained many [[Slander and libel|false statements]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/newyorker.htm |title= Sidis vs New Yorker |website= Sidis.net |date=February 29, 2008 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> Under the title \"Where Are They Now?\", [[James Thurber]] pseudonymously described Sidis's life as lonely, in a \"hall bedroom in Boston's shabby South End\".<ref>{{Cite book|title= Journalism and the Debate Over Privacy|last=LaMay|first=Craig L.|series=LEA's Communication Series| publisher= Lawrence Erlbaum Associates, Inc.|location= Mahwah, New Jersey |year=2003|isbn=978-0-8058-4626-3 |page=63}}</ref> Lower courts had dismissed Sidis as a [[public figure]] with no right to challenge personal publicity. He lost an appeal of an [[invasion of privacy]] lawsuit at the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] in 1940 over the same article. Judge [[Charles Edward Clark]] expressed sympathy for Sidis, who claimed that the publication had exposed him to \"public scorn, ridicule, and contempt\" and caused him \"grievous mental anguish [and] humiliation,\" but found that the court was not disposed to \"afford to all the intimate details of private life an absolute immunity from the prying of the press\".<ref name=\"seitz\">{{cite web| url= http://hiqnews.megafoundation.org/William_Sidis.htm |title=Review of Amy Wallace, ''The Prodigy'' (1986) |first= Robert N. |last=Seitz |work=High IQ News |year=2002 |accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSidis died from a [[cerebral hemorrhage]] in 1944 in Boston at age 46.<ref>{{cite web| work= [[Boston Traveler]] |url= http://www.sidis.net/smithletter.htm |first= Shirley |last= Smith| title= Letter to the Editor |via=Sidis.net |date=July 19, 1944 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> His father had died from the same malady in 1923 at age 56.\n\n==Publications and subjects of research==\nFrom writings on cosmology, to writings on American Indian history, to ''Notes on the Collection of Transfers,'' and several purported lost texts on anthropology, philology, and transportation systems, Sidis covered a broad range of subjects. Some of his ideas concerned [[Time reversibility|cosmological reversibility]]<ref name =Reversibility>{{Cite journal | title = The Animate and the Inanimate | last = Sidis | first = William James | publisher = The Gorham Press | year = 1925 | place = Boston| url = http://www.sidis.net/ANIMContents.htm }}</ref> and \"social continuity\".<ref name =ContinuityNews>{{cite web| last = Sidis | first = William James | title = Continuity News | url = http://www.sidis.net/continuitynewsmenu.htm |via= Sidis.net}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Animate and the Inanimate]]'' (1925), Sidis predicted the existence of regions of space where the [[second law of thermodynamics]] operated in reverse to the temporal direction that we experience in our local area. Everything outside of what we would today call a [[galaxy]] would be such a region. Sidis claimed that the matter in this region would not generate light. Sidis's ''[[The Tribes and the States]]'' (ca. 1935) employs the [[pseudonym]] \"John W. Shattuck\", purporting to give a 100,000-year history of the [[Prehistoric migration and settlement of the Americas from Asia|Settlement of the Americas]], from prehistoric times to 1828.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/TSContents.htm |title=The Tribes and the States, Table of Contents |publisher=Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> In this text, he suggests that \"there were red men at one time in Europe as well as in America\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/TSChap1.htm |title=The Tribes and the States, Native American history |publisher=Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSidis was also a \"[[railfan|peridromophile]]\", a term he coined for people fascinated with transportation research and [[streetcar]] systems. He wrote a treatise on streetcar transfers under the pseudonym of \"Frank Folupa\" that identified means of increasing public transport usage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/TransfersContents.htm |title=Notes on the Collection of Transfers |via= Sidis.net |date=June 20, 1926 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1930, Sidis received a patent for a rotary [[perpetual calendar]] that took into account [[leap years]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents?hl=en&lr=&vid=USPAT1784117&id=lFFZAAAAEBAJ |title=Perpetual Calendar |publisher=United States Patent Office |date=December 9, 1930 |accessdate=September 6, 2013 | ref=harv }}</ref>\n\n===Vendergood language===\nSidis created a [[constructed language]] called Vendergood in his second book, the ''Book of Vendergood'', which he wrote at the age of 8. The language was mostly based on [[Latin]] and [[Greek language|Greek]], but also drew on [[German language|German]] and [[French language|French]] and other [[Romance languages]].<ref name= Wallace /> It distinguished between eight [[Grammatical mood|moods]]: [[indicative]], [[Irrealis_mood#Potential|potential]], [[imperative absolute]], [[subjunctive]], [[Imperative mood|imperative]], [[infinitive]], [[optative]], and Sidis's own strongeable.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|41}} One of its chapters is titled \"Imperfect and Future Indicative Active\". Other parts explain the origin of Roman numerals. It uses [[Duodecimal#Advocacy and \"dozenalism\"|base 12]] instead of base 10:\n \n* eis \u2013 one\n* duet \u2013 two\n* tre \u2013 three\n* guar \u2013 four\n* quin \u2013 five\n* sex \u2013 six\n* sep \u2013 seven\n* oo(oe?) \u2013 eight\n* non \u2013 nine\n* ecem \u2013 ten\n* elevenos \u2013 eleven\n* dec \u2013 twelve\n* eidec (eis, dec) \u2013 thirteen\n \nMost of the examples are presented in the form of tests:\n \n# Do I love the young man? = Amevo (-)ne the neania?\n# The bowman obscures. = The toxoteis obscurit.\n# I am learning Vendergood. = (Euni) disceuo Vendergood.\n# What do you learn? (sing.). = Quen diseois-nar?\n# I obscure ten farmers. = Obscureuo ecem agrieolai.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|42\u201343}}\n\n==Legacy==\nAfter his death, Helena Sidis claimed that her brother had an IQ reported in Abraham Sperling's 1946 book ''Psychology for the Millions'' as \"the very highest that had ever been obtained\",<ref name=\"sperling\" /> but later authors found that some of his biographers, such as [[Amy Wallace]], exaggerated how high his IQ actually was and exactly what Sperling had claimed.<ref name=ioipj>{{cite web |url= http://www.thelogics.org/thelogicswilliamsidissmartestmanonearth.html|title=The Logics \u2013 Was William James Sidis the Smartest Man on Earth|publisher=Thelogics.org|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Sperling actually wrote:<ref name= \"sperling\">{{cite book|last=Sperling |first=Abraham Paul |title=Psychology for the Millions |url= https://archive.org/stream/psychologyforthe032777mbp/psychologyforthe032777mbp_djvu.txt |year=1947 |publisher= Frederick Fell |location=New York |pages=332\u2013339 |ref=harv |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Helena Sidis told me that a few years before his death, her brother Bill took an intelligence test with a psychologist. His score was the highest that had ever been obtained. In terms of IQ, the psychologist related that the figure would be between 250 and 300. Late in life William Sidis took general intelligence tests for Civil Service positions in New York and Boston. His phenomenal ratings are matter of record.}}\n\nIt has been acknowledged that Helena and William's mother Sarah had developed a reputation of exaggerated claims about the Sidis family.<ref name=ioipj /> Helena had also falsely claimed that the Civil Service exam William took in 1933 was an IQ test and that his ranking of 254 was instead an IQ score of 254.<ref name=ioipj /> It is speculated that the number \"254\" was actually William's placement on the list after he passed the Civil Service exam, as he stated in a letter sent to his family.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gowdy| first1=Larry Neal|title=Myths, Facts, Lies, and Humor About William James Sidis \u2013 Part One| url= http://www.thelogics.org/thelogicswilliamsidismyths1.html |website= thelogics.org |accessdate= March 4, 2016|date=October 20, 2013|quote=A letter written by William Sidis stated that he had taken a civil service exam, that he passed the state clerical exam, and that he was number 254 on the list; \"not so encouraging\". It may never be known if Sidis actually did take an IQ test, and it may never be known if the 250\u2013300 number arrived from Sidis' placement in the job pool.}}</ref> Helena also claimed that \"Billy knew all the languages in the world, while my father only knew 27. I wonder if there were any Billy didn't know.\"<ref name=ioipj /> This claim was not backed by any other source outside the Sidis family, and Sarah Sidis also made an improbable claim in her 1950 book ''The Sidis Story'' that William could learn a language in just one day.<ref name=ioipj /> Boris Sidis had once dismissed tests of intelligence as \"silly, pedantic, absurd, and grossly misleading\".<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.sidis.net/fnappref.htm |title=Foundations of Normal and Abnormal psychology |website=Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> Regardless of the exaggerations, Sidis is judged by other high IQ peers such as MIT Physics professor [[Daniel Frost Comstock]] and American mathematician [[Norbert Wiener]] (who wrote in his autobiography about his contemporary at Harvard, Sidis) to have had real ability.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.sidis.net/newyorker3.htm |via= sidis.net| title= Where Are They Now? April Fool!| author2= (James Thurber)| first= Jared L. |last= Manley |work= The New Yorker| date= August 14, 1937| pages= 22\u201326| access-date= February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name= Wallace />{{rp|54}}<ref>{{cite book| url= https://www.sidis.net/Lila.htm |via= sidis.net| title= Lila| first= Robert M.| last= Pirsig| date= 1991 | access-date= February 13, 2020 |page= 55}}</ref>\n\nSidis' life and work, particularly his ideas about [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]], are extensively discussed in [[Robert M. Pirsig]]'s book ''[[Lila: An Inquiry into Morals]]'' (1991).<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/lila-robert-pirsig/1111847927|title=Lila: An Inquiry into Morals |last=| first=| website= barnesandnoble.com| publisher= Barnes & Noble|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> Sidis is also discussed in ''Ex-Prodigy'', an autobiography by mathematician Norbert Wiener (1894\u20131964), who was a prodigy himself.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/ex-prodigy|title=Ex-Prodigy|last=|first=|website=The MIT Press| language=en| access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Danish author Morten Brask wrote a novel as a fictional account based on Sidis' life; ''The Perfect Life of William Sidis'' was published in Denmark in 2011. Another novel based on his biography was published by the German author Klaus C\u00e4sar Zehrer in 2017.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Das Genie|last=Zehrer|first=Klaus C\u00e4sar|publisher=Diogenes Verlag |year= 2017|isbn=978-3-257-06998-3|location=Z\u00fcrich|pages= |language= German}}</ref>\n\n===In education discussions===\nThe debate about Sidis' manner of upbringing occurred within a larger discourse about the best way to educate children. Newspapers criticized Boris Sidis' [[child-rearing]] methods. Most educators of the day believed that schools should expose children to common experiences to create good citizens. Most psychologists thought intelligence was hereditary, a position that precluded early childhood education at home.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Curing the Disease of Precocity |last= Kett |first=Joseph F. |journal=The American Journal of Sociology |issn=0002-9602 |volume=84 |issue=suppl |pages= S183\u2013S211 |year=1978 |doi=10.1086/649240 |jstor=3083227 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe difficulties Sidis encountered in dealing with the social structure of a collegiate setting may have shaped opinion against allowing such children to rapidly advance through higher education in his day. Research indicates that a challenging curriculum can relieve social and emotional difficulties commonly experienced by gifted children.<ref>{{cite book| title= The Social and Emotional Development of Gifted Children: What Do We Know| editor-first1= Maureen| editor-last1= Neihart| editor-first2= Sally M.| editor-last2= Reis| editor-first3= Nancy M. |editor-last3= Robinson| editor-first4= Sidney M.| editor-last4= Moon| publisher= [[National Association for Gifted Children]] (Prufrock Press, Inc.)| year= 2002| pages= 286\u2013287}}</ref> Embracing these findings, several colleges now have procedures for early entrance. The [[Davidson Institute for Talent Development]] has developed a guidebook on the topic.<ref>{{cite book |title= Considering the Options: A Guidebook for Investigating Early College Entrance| url= http://print.ditd.org/young_scholars/Guidebooks/Davidson_Guidebook_EarlyCollege_Parents.pdf |publisher=Print.ditd.org |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSidis was portrayed derisively in the press of the day. ''[[The New York Times]]'', for example, described him as \"a wonderfully successful result of a scientific forcing experiment\".<ref name=\"nyt1909\">{{cite news|title=Sidis Could Read at Two Years Old; Youngest Harvard Undergraduate Under Father's Scientific Forcing Process Almost from Birth. Good Typewriter at Four; At 5 Composed Text Book on Anatomy, in Grammar School at 6, Then Studied German, French, Latin, and Russian.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 18, 1909|page=7}}</ref> His mother later maintained that newspaper accounts of her son bore little resemblance to him.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{Cite book|last=Wallace|first=Amy|title=The Prodigy: a Biography of William James Sidis, America's Greatest Child Prodigy|location=New York|publisher=E.P. Dutton & Co.|year=1986|isbn=0-525-24404-2|url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/prodigy00wall}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sidis.net Sidis Archives] at Sidis.net\n* [http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/1363/why-did-william-sidis-the-worlds-2nd-smartest-human-achieve-so-little-in-life Article about William James Sidis] at [[The Straight Dope]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sidis, William James}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:American anthropologists]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American conscientious objectors]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American pacifists]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American socialists]]\n[[Category:American spiritualists]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Rice University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rice University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|American child prodigy}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = William James Sidis\n|other_names = {{unordered list|John W. Shattuck|Frank Folupa|Parker Greene|Jacob Marmor}}\n|image = William James Sidis 1914.jpg\n|caption = William James Sidis at his [[Harvard University|Harvard]] graduation (1914)\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1898|4|1}}\n|birth_place = [[Manhattan, New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|1944|7|17|1898|4|1}}\n|death_place = [[South Boston]], [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States\n|alma_mater = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[Rice University]]\n|notable_works = {{unordered list|''[[The Animate and the Inanimate]]'' (1925)|''[[The Tribes and the States]]'' ({{circa|1935|lk=no}})}}\n}}\n\n'''William James Sidis''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|a\u026a|d|\u026a|s}}; April 1, 1898 \u2013 July 17, 1944) was an American [[child prodigy]] with exceptional mathematical and linguistic skills. He is notable for his 1920 book ''[[The Animate and the Inanimate]]'', in which he postulates the existence of [[dark matter]], [[entropy]], and the origin of life in the context of [[thermodynamics]]. Sidis was raised in a particular manner by his father, psychologist [[Boris Sidis]], who wished his son to be gifted. Sidis first became famous for his precocity and later for his [[Eccentricity (behavior)|eccentricity]] and withdrawal from public life. Eventually, he avoided mathematics altogether, writing on other subjects under a number of [[pseudonym]]s. He entered [[Harvard University|Harvard]] at age 11 and, as an adult, was claimed to have an extremely high IQ, and to be conversant in about 25 languages and dialects. Some of these claims have not been verified, but many of his contemporaries, including [[Norbert Wiener]], [[Daniel Frost Comstock]] and [[William James]], supported the assertion that he was extremely intelligent.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Parents and upbringing (1898\u20131908)===\nWilliam James Sidis was born to Jewish emigrants from Ukraine,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayifoundout.com/index.php/2013/12/genius-among-us-sad-story-william-j-sidis/|title=A Genius Among Us: The Sad Story of William J. Sidis|date=December 6, 2013|newspaper=Today I Found Out|language=en-US|access-date=December 9, 2016}}</ref> on April 1, 1898, in [[New York City]]. His father, [[Boris Sidis]], PhD, M.D., had emigrated in 1887 to escape political persecution.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|2\u20134}} His mother, Sarah (Mandelbaum) Sidis, M.D., and her family had fled the [[pogrom]]s in the late 1880s.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|7}} Sarah attended [[Boston University]] and graduated from its [[Boston University School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoint.org/history/king/3-05.htm |title=History of Homeopathy and Its Institutions in America By William Harvey King, M.D., LL.D. Presented by Sylvain Cazalet |publisher=Homeoint.org |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWilliam was named after his godfather, Boris' friend and colleague, the American philosopher [[William James]]. Boris was a [[psychiatrist]] and published numerous books and articles, performing pioneering work in [[psychopathology|abnormal psychology]]. He was a [[polyglot]], and his son William would become one at a young age.\n\nSidis's parents believed in nurturing a [[wiktionary:precocious|precocious]] and fearless love of knowledge (but their methods of parenting were criticized in the media and retrospectively<ref name=\"nyt1909\"/><ref name= Wallace />{{rp|281, Epilogue}}). Sidis could read ''[[The New York Times]]'' at 18 months.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|23}} By age eight, he had reportedly taught himself eight languages ([[Latin]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[French language|French]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[German language|German]], [[Hebrew]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and [[Armenian language|Armenian]]) and invented another, which he called \"Vendergood\".\n\n===Harvard University and college life (1909\u20131915)===\nAlthough the University had previously refused to let his father enroll him at age 9 because he was still a child, Sidis set a record in 1909 by becoming the youngest person to enroll at [[Harvard University]]. In early 1910, Sidis' mastery of higher mathematics was such that he lectured the Harvard Mathematical Club on [[Four-dimensional space|four-dimensional bodies]] which brought him nationwide attention.<ref>{{cite journal| url= https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1977-31409-001| via= APA.org| title= William James Sidis, the broken twig| last= Montour| first= Kathleen| work= [[American Psychologist]]| volume= 32| number= 4| pages= 265\u2013279| doi= 10.1037/0003-066X.32.4.265| date= April 1977| access-date= February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Wonderful Boys of History Compared With Sidis. All Except Macaulay Showed Special Ability in Mathematics. Instances of Boys Having 'Universal Genius' |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E0CE2DC1139E333A25755C1A9679C946196D6CF |date=January 16, 1910| page= SM11| work=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate= November 26, 2014}}</ref> Notable child prodigy, [[cybernetics]] pioneer [[Norbert Wiener]], who also attended Harvard at the time and knew Sidis later stated in his book ''Ex-Prodigy'': \"The talk would have done credit to a first or second-year graduate student of any age...talk represented the triumph of the unaided efforts of a very brilliant child.\"<ref>{{cite web| title= A Review of Kathleen Montour's William James Sidis, The Broken Twig | first= Doug| last= Renselle| website= Quantonics.com| publisher= | url= http://www.quantonics.com/Review_of_WJS_The_Broken_Twig.html| access-date= February 13, 2020}}</ref> MIT Physics professor [[Daniel F. Comstock]] was full of praises: \"[[Karl Friedrich Gauss]] is the only example in history, of all prodigies, whom Sidis resembles. I predict that young Sidis will be a great astronomical mathematician. He will evolve new theories and invent new ways of calculating astronomical phenomena. I believe he will be a great mathematician, the leader in that science in the future.\"<ref name= Wallace>{{cite book | last = Wallace | first = Amy  | title = The prodigy: a biography of William James Sidis, the world's greatest child prodigy | publisher = Macmillan | location = London | date = 1986 | isbn = 9780333432235}}</ref> Sidis began taking a full-time course load in 1910 and earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree, ''[[cum laude]]'', on June 18, 1914, at age 16.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.sidis.net/transcript1.jpg|title=Harvard College, 1952 |via= Sidis.net |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nShortly after graduation, he told reporters that he wanted to live the perfect life, which to him meant living in seclusion. He granted an interview to a reporter from the ''[[Boston Herald]]''. The paper reported Sidis's vows to remain [[Celibacy|celibate]] and never to marry, as he said women did not appeal to him. Later he developed a strong affection for a young woman named [[Martha Foley]]. He later enrolled at [[Harvard Graduate School of Arts and Sciences]].\n\nAccording to ''The Prodigy: a Biography of William James Sidis'', he briefly served at the [[League of Nations]] before leaving because U.S. president [[Woodrow Wilson]] would not withdraw troops deployed during [[World War I|the Great War]]. He was outspoken about his [[pacifism]].\n\n===Teaching and further education (1915\u20131919)===\nAfter a group of Harvard students threatened Sidis physically, his parents secured him a job at the [[William Marsh Rice]] Institute for the Advancement of Letters, Science, and Art (now [[Rice University]]) in [[Houston, Texas]], as a mathematics teaching assistant. He arrived at Rice in December 1915 at the age of 17. He was a graduate fellow working toward his doctorate.\n\nSidis taught three classes: [[Euclidean geometry]], [[non-Euclidean geometry]], and freshman math (he wrote a textbook for the Euclidean geometry course in Greek).<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|112}} After less than a year, frustrated with the department, his teaching requirements, and his treatment by students older than himself, Sidis left his post and returned to New England. When a friend later asked him why he had left, he replied, \"I never knew why they gave me the job in the first place\u2014I'm not much of a teacher. I didn't leave: I was asked to go.\" Sidis abandoned his pursuit of a graduate degree in mathematics and enrolled at the [[Harvard Law School]] in September 1916, but withdrew in good standing in his final year in March 1919.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/transcripts.htm |title=Harvard Transcripts |via= Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Politics and arrest (1919\u20131921)===\nIn 1919, shortly after his withdrawal from law school, Sidis was arrested for participating in a socialist [[May Day]] parade in Boston that turned violent. He was sentenced to 18 months in prison under the [[Sedition Act of 1918]] by Roxbury Municipal Court Judge [[Albert F Hayden]]. Sidis' arrest featured prominently in newspapers, as his early graduation from Harvard had garnered considerable local celebrity status. During the trial, Sidis stated that he had been a [[conscientious objector]] to the [[World War I]] draft, was a [[socialism|socialist]], and did not believe in a god like the \"big boss of the Christians,\" but rather in something that is in a way apart from a human being.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sidis Gets Year and Half in Jail|url=http://www.sidis.net/herald1919.htm |accessdate= January 12, 2018 |work= [[Boston Herald]] |date=May 14, 1919|quote='Do you believe in a god?' 'No.' Atty. Connolly then asked the court what God he meant, whereupon Judge Hayden replied, God Almighty. Here Sidis said that the kind of a God that he did not believe in was the 'big boss of the Christians,' adding that he believed in something that is in a way apart from a human being.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mahony |first1=Dan |title=Frequently Asked Questions About W. J. Sidis |url= http://www.sidis.net/sidisfaq.htm |accessdate=January 12, 2018|quote=\"Was he religious? 'He espoused no religion, but said that... the kind of a God he did not believe in was the \"big boss of the Christians\", adding that he believed in something that is in a way apart from a human being (Boston Herald, May 14, 1919).'\"}}</ref> He later developed his own [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] philosophy based on individual rights and \"the American social continuity\".<ref name = Libertarian>{{Cite journal| last = Sidis | first = William James | title = Libertarian | journal = Continuity News | issue = 2 | page = 4 |date = June 1938| location = Cambridge, Massachusetts| url = http://www.sidis.net/libertarian.htm }}</ref><ref name =\"TheConceptof 'Rights'\">{{Cite journal | last = Sidis | first = William James | title = The Concept of Rights | publisher = American Independence Society | url = http://www.sidis.net/rights2.htm |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> His father arranged with the district attorney to keep Sidis out of prison before his appeal came to trial; his parents, instead, held him in their sanatorium in New Hampshire for a year. They took him to [[California]], where he spent another year.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/railroading.htm |title=Railroading in the Past |via= Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> While at the sanatorium, his parents set about \"reforming\" him and threatened him with transfer to an insane asylum.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n===Later life (1921\u20131944)===\nAfter returning to the East Coast in 1921, Sidis was determined to live an independent and private life. He only took work running adding machines or other fairly menial tasks. He worked in New York City and became estranged from his parents. It took years before he was cleared legally to return to Massachusetts, and he was concerned about his risk of arrest for years. He obsessively collected streetcar [[Transfer (public transit)|transfers]], wrote self-published periodicals, and taught small circles of interested friends his version of American history. In 1933, Sidis passed a Civil Service exam in New York, but scored a low ranking of 254.<ref name=ioipj /> In a private letter, Sidis wrote that this was \"not so encouraging\".<ref name=ioipj /> In 1935, he wrote an unpublished manuscript, ''[http://www.mortenbrask.com/wp-content/uploads/The-tribes-and-the-states-SIDIS.pdf The Tribes and the States]'', which traces [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] contributions to [[American democracy]].<ref>{{cite journal| title= William James Sidis' 'Tribes and States': An Unpublished Exploration of Native American Contributions to Democracy| last= Johansen| first= Bruce E.| work= [[Northeast Indian Quarterly]]| volume= 6 |number= 3| pages= 24\u201329 |date= Fall 1989| url= https://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ404329| via= eric.ed.gov| access-date= }}</ref>\n\nIn 1944, Sidis won a settlement from ''[[The New Yorker]]'' for an article published in 1937.<ref>{{Cite journal |last= Bates |first=Stephen |year=2011 |title=The Prodigy and the Press: William James Sidis, Anti-Intellectualism, and Standards of Success |journal=[[Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly|J&MC Quarterly]] |issn=1077-6990 |volume=88 |issue=2 |pages=374\u2013397 |doi=10.1177/107769901108800209 |ref=harv }}</ref> He had alleged it contained many [[Slander and libel|false statements]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/newyorker.htm |title= Sidis vs New Yorker |website= Sidis.net |date=February 29, 2008 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> Under the title \"Where Are They Now?\", [[James Thurber]] pseudonymously described Sidis's life as lonely, in a \"hall bedroom in Boston's shabby South End\".<ref>{{Cite book|title= Journalism and the Debate Over Privacy|last=LaMay|first=Craig L.|series=LEA's Communication Series| publisher= Lawrence Erlbaum Associates, Inc.|location= Mahwah, New Jersey |year=2003|isbn=978-0-8058-4626-3 |page=63}}</ref> Lower courts had dismissed Sidis as a [[public figure]] with no right to challenge personal publicity. He lost an appeal of an [[invasion of privacy]] lawsuit at the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] in 1940 over the same article. Judge [[Charles Edward Clark]] expressed sympathy for Sidis, who claimed that the publication had exposed him to \"public scorn, ridicule, and contempt\" and caused him \"grievous mental anguish [and] humiliation,\" but found that the court was not disposed to \"afford to all the intimate details of private life an absolute immunity from the prying of the press\".<ref name=\"seitz\">{{cite web| url= http://hiqnews.megafoundation.org/William_Sidis.htm |title=Review of Amy Wallace, ''The Prodigy'' (1986) |first= Robert N. |last=Seitz |work=High IQ News |year=2002 |accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSidis died from a [[cerebral hemorrhage]] in 1944 in Boston at age 46.<ref>{{cite web| work= [[Boston Traveler]] |url= http://www.sidis.net/smithletter.htm |first= Shirley |last= Smith| title= Letter to the Editor |via=Sidis.net |date=July 19, 1944 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> His father had died from the same malady in 1923 at age 56.\n\n==Publications and subjects of research==\nFrom writings on cosmology, to writings on American Indian history, to ''Notes on the Collection of Transfers,'' and several purported lost texts on anthropology, philology, and transportation systems, Sidis covered a broad range of subjects. Some of his ideas concerned [[Time reversibility|cosmological reversibility]]<ref name =Reversibility>{{Cite journal | title = The Animate and the Inanimate | last = Sidis | first = William James | publisher = The Gorham Press | year = 1925 | place = Boston| url = http://www.sidis.net/ANIMContents.htm }}</ref> and \"social continuity\".<ref name =ContinuityNews>{{cite web| last = Sidis | first = William James | title = Continuity News | url = http://www.sidis.net/continuitynewsmenu.htm |via= Sidis.net}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Animate and the Inanimate]]'' (1925), Sidis predicted the existence of regions of space where the [[second law of thermodynamics]] operated in reverse to the temporal direction that we experience in our local area. Everything outside of what we would today call a [[galaxy]] would be such a region. Sidis claimed that the matter in this region would not generate light. Sidis's ''[[The Tribes and the States]]'' (ca. 1935) employs the [[pseudonym]] \"John W. Shattuck\", purporting to give a 100,000-year history of the [[Prehistoric migration and settlement of the Americas from Asia|Settlement of the Americas]], from prehistoric times to 1828.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/TSContents.htm |title=The Tribes and the States, Table of Contents |publisher=Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> In this text, he suggests that \"there were red men at one time in Europe as well as in America\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/TSChap1.htm |title=The Tribes and the States, Native American history |publisher=Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSidis was also a \"[[railfan|peridromophile]]\", a term he coined for people fascinated with transportation research and [[streetcar]] systems. He wrote a treatise on streetcar transfers under the pseudonym of \"Frank Folupa\" that identified means of increasing public transport usage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidis.net/TransfersContents.htm |title=Notes on the Collection of Transfers |via= Sidis.net |date=June 20, 1926 |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1930, Sidis received a patent for a rotary [[perpetual calendar]] that took into account [[leap years]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents?hl=en&lr=&vid=USPAT1784117&id=lFFZAAAAEBAJ |title=Perpetual Calendar |publisher=United States Patent Office |date=December 9, 1930 |accessdate=September 6, 2013 | ref=harv }}</ref>\n\n===Vendergood language===\nSidis created a [[constructed language]] called Vendergood in his second book, the ''Book of Vendergood'', which he wrote at the age of 8. The language was mostly based on [[Latin]] and [[Greek language|Greek]], but also drew on [[German language|German]] and [[French language|French]] and other [[Romance languages]].<ref name= Wallace /> It distinguished between eight [[Grammatical mood|moods]]: [[indicative]], [[Irrealis_mood#Potential|potential]], [[imperative absolute]], [[subjunctive]], [[Imperative mood|imperative]], [[infinitive]], [[optative]], and Sidis's own strongeable.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|41}} One of its chapters is titled \"Imperfect and Future Indicative Active\". Other parts explain the origin of Roman numerals. It uses [[Duodecimal#Advocacy and \"dozenalism\"|base 12]] instead of base 10:\n \n* eis \u2013 one\n* duet \u2013 two\n* tre \u2013 three\n* guar \u2013 four\n* quin \u2013 five\n* sex \u2013 six\n* sep \u2013 seven\n* oo(oe?) \u2013 eight\n* non \u2013 nine\n* ecem \u2013 ten\n* elevenos \u2013 eleven\n* dec \u2013 twelve\n* eidec (eis, dec) \u2013 thirteen\n \nMost of the examples are presented in the form of tests:\n \n# Do I love the young man? = Amevo (-)ne the neania?\n# The bowman obscures. = The toxoteis obscurit.\n# I am learning Vendergood. = (Euni) disceuo Vendergood.\n# What do you learn? (sing.). = Quen diseois-nar?\n# I obscure ten farmers. = Obscureuo ecem agrieolai.<ref name= Wallace />{{rp|42\u201343}}\n\n==Legacy==\nAfter his death, Helena Sidis claimed that her brother had an IQ reported in Abraham Sperling's 1946 book ''Psychology for the Millions'' as \"the very highest that had ever been obtained\",<ref name=\"sperling\" /> but later authors found that some of his biographers, such as [[Amy Wallace]], exaggerated how high his IQ actually was and exactly what Sperling had claimed.<ref name=ioipj>{{cite web |url= http://www.thelogics.org/thelogicswilliamsidissmartestmanonearth.html|title=The Logics \u2013 Was William James Sidis the Smartest Man on Earth|publisher=Thelogics.org|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Sperling actually wrote:<ref name= \"sperling\">{{cite book|last=Sperling |first=Abraham Paul |title=Psychology for the Millions |url= https://archive.org/stream/psychologyforthe032777mbp/psychologyforthe032777mbp_djvu.txt |year=1947 |publisher= Frederick Fell |location=New York |pages=332\u2013339 |ref=harv |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Helena Sidis told me that a few years before his death, her brother Bill took an intelligence test with a psychologist. His score was the highest that had ever been obtained. In terms of IQ, the psychologist related that the figure would be between 250 and 300. Late in life William Sidis took general intelligence tests for Civil Service positions in New York and Boston. His phenomenal ratings are matter of record.}}\n\nIt has been acknowledged that Helena and William's mother Sarah had developed a reputation of exaggerated claims about the Sidis family.<ref name=ioipj /> Helena had also falsely claimed that the Civil Service exam William took in 1933 was an IQ test and that his ranking of 254 was instead an IQ score of 254.<ref name=ioipj /> It is speculated that the number \"254\" was actually William's placement on the list after he passed the Civil Service exam, as he stated in a letter sent to his family.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gowdy| first1=Larry Neal|title=Myths, Facts, Lies, and Humor About William James Sidis \u2013 Part One| url= http://www.thelogics.org/thelogicswilliamsidismyths1.html |website= thelogics.org |accessdate= March 4, 2016|date=October 20, 2013|quote=A letter written by William Sidis stated that he had taken a civil service exam, that he passed the state clerical exam, and that he was number 254 on the list; \"not so encouraging\". It may never be known if Sidis actually did take an IQ test, and it may never be known if the 250\u2013300 number arrived from Sidis' placement in the job pool.}}</ref> Helena also claimed that \"Billy knew all the languages in the world, while my father only knew 27. I wonder if there were any Billy didn't know.\"<ref name=ioipj /> This claim was not backed by any other source outside the Sidis family, and Sarah Sidis also made an improbable claim in her 1950 book ''The Sidis Story'' that William could learn a language in just one day.<ref name=ioipj /> Boris Sidis had once dismissed tests of intelligence as \"silly, pedantic, absurd, and grossly misleading\".<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.sidis.net/fnappref.htm |title=Foundations of Normal and Abnormal psychology |website=Sidis.net |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2011}}</ref> Regardless of the exaggerations, Sidis is judged by other high IQ peers such as MIT Physics professor [[Daniel Frost Comstock]] and American mathematician [[Norbert Wiener]] (who wrote in his autobiography about his contemporary at Harvard, Sidis) to have had real ability.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.sidis.net/newyorker3.htm |via= sidis.net| title= Where Are They Now? April Fool!| author2= (James Thurber)| first= Jared L. |last= Manley |work= The New Yorker| date= August 14, 1937| pages= 22\u201326| access-date= February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name= Wallace />{{rp|54}}<ref>{{cite book| url= https://www.sidis.net/Lila.htm |via= sidis.net| title= Lila| first= Robert M.| last= Pirsig| date= 1991 | access-date= February 13, 2020 |page= 55}}</ref>\n\nSidis' life and work, particularly his ideas about [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]], are extensively discussed in [[Robert M. Pirsig]]'s book ''[[Lila: An Inquiry into Morals]]'' (1991).<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/lila-robert-pirsig/1111847927|title=Lila: An Inquiry into Morals |last=| first=| website= barnesandnoble.com| publisher= Barnes & Noble|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> Sidis is also discussed in ''Ex-Prodigy'', an autobiography by mathematician Norbert Wiener (1894\u20131964), who was a prodigy himself.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/ex-prodigy|title=Ex-Prodigy|last=|first=|website=The MIT Press| language=en| access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Danish author Morten Brask wrote a novel as a fictional account based on Sidis' life; ''The Perfect Life of William Sidis'' was published in Denmark in 2011. Another novel based on his biography was published by the German author Klaus C\u00e4sar Zehrer in 2017.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Das Genie|last=Zehrer|first=Klaus C\u00e4sar|publisher=Diogenes Verlag |year= 2017|isbn=978-3-257-06998-3|location=Z\u00fcrich|pages= |language= German}}</ref>\n\n===In education discussions===\nThe debate about Sidis' manner of upbringing occurred within a larger discourse about the best way to educate children. Newspapers criticized Boris Sidis' [[child-rearing]] methods. Most educators of the day believed that schools should expose children to common experiences to create good citizens. Most psychologists thought intelligence was hereditary, a position that precluded early childhood education at home.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Curing the Disease of Precocity |last= Kett |first=Joseph F. |journal=The American Journal of Sociology |issn=0002-9602 |volume=84 |issue=suppl |pages= S183\u2013S211 |year=1978 |doi=10.1086/649240 |jstor=3083227 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe difficulties Sidis encountered in dealing with the social structure of a collegiate setting may have shaped opinion against allowing such children to rapidly advance through higher education in his day. Research indicates that a challenging curriculum can relieve social and emotional difficulties commonly experienced by gifted children.<ref>{{cite book| title= The Social and Emotional Development of Gifted Children: What Do We Know| editor-first1= Maureen| editor-last1= Neihart| editor-first2= Sally M.| editor-last2= Reis| editor-first3= Nancy M. |editor-last3= Robinson| editor-first4= Sidney M.| editor-last4= Moon| publisher= [[National Association for Gifted Children]] (Prufrock Press, Inc.)| year= 2002| pages= 286\u2013287}}</ref> Embracing these findings, several colleges now have procedures for early entrance. The [[Davidson Institute for Talent Development]] has developed a guidebook on the topic.<ref>{{cite book |title= Considering the Options: A Guidebook for Investigating Early College Entrance| url= http://print.ditd.org/young_scholars/Guidebooks/Davidson_Guidebook_EarlyCollege_Parents.pdf |publisher=Print.ditd.org |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSidis was portrayed derisively in the press of the day. ''[[The New York Times]]'', for example, described him as \"a wonderfully successful result of a scientific forcing experiment\".<ref name=\"nyt1909\">{{cite news|title=Sidis Could Read at Two Years Old; Youngest Harvard Undergraduate Under Father's Scientific Forcing Process Almost from Birth. Good Typewriter at Four; At 5 Composed Text Book on Anatomy, in Grammar School at 6, Then Studied German, French, Latin, and Russian.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 18, 1909|page=7}}</ref> His mother later maintained that newspaper accounts of her son bore little resemblance to him.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{Cite book|last=Wallace|first=Amy|title=The Prodigy: a Biography of William James Sidis, America's Greatest Child Prodigy|location=New York|publisher=E.P. Dutton & Co.|year=1986|isbn=0-525-24404-2|url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/prodigy00wall}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sidis.net Sidis Archives] at Sidis.net\n* [http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/1363/why-did-william-sidis-the-worlds-2nd-smartest-human-achieve-so-little-in-life Article about William James Sidis] at [[The Straight Dope]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sidis, William James}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:American anthropologists]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American conscientious objectors]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American pacifists]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American socialists]]\n[[Category:American spiritualists]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Rice University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rice University faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Speccss", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_James_Sidis"}
{"title_page": "Herki", "text_new": "{{short description|Kurdish tribe}}\n'''Herki''', also spelled '''Harki''', is the second largest tribe in [[Kurdistan]] after [[Jaff (people)|Jaff]]. The largest part of this tribe live in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] and a significant number live in [[Iranian Kurdistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/harki|title=HARKI \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==Sub-tribes==\nThe Herkis are divided in three sub-tribes: Menda, Sida and Serhati. The Herki dialect belongs to the [[Kurmanji]] dialect.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/13/countries/Turk.html |website=ethnologue.com |publisher=Summer Institute of Linguistics |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Lifestyle==\nThe Herkis lived mostly a [[nomadic]] life with their herds; however, this changed a lot after 1920 and the [[Treaty of S\u00e8vres]]. The new hand-drawn borders of Iran, Iraq, Syria and Turkey hindered [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] tribes to continue their way of life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iraq: Kurdish militia called Harqi (Harki, Herki, Harkki, Harqees) allied; current activities; its relationship with the Iraqi government; tribal affiliations |url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3df4be4c20.html |website=refworld.org |publisher=UNHCR |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>The [[Turkish Gendarmerie]] was famous for its brutality against nomads and their herds. This led to many [[Kurdish tribes]] besides the Herkis leaving their nomadic lifestyle and settled in villages which they had before only used during the winter. The nomadic and free lifestyle they had, was taken from them. \n\nThe new borders soon had a major impact on every aspect of the Kurdish life. For Herkis and many other Kurds that meant that areas which had belonged to them and their herds were taken from them, and they could not move freely like their forefathers had done for a century. They had to decide in which country to settle, which is the reason why Herkis and many other Kurdish tribes can be found dispersed in Iran, Iraq and Turkey, but still be of the same tribe.\n\nIn 1989 they counted some 20,000 people, living between [[Urmia]] and [[Rawanduz]], one if the largest remaining groups of pastoral herders. On their regular movement they brought salt from Iran to Iraq and carried wheat and barley back to Iran.<ref>{{cite book|title=Kurdish Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zc0MAQAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Cultural Survival, Incorporated|pages=34-40}}</ref>\n\nToday, the Herkis live in Iranian Kurdistan around and in [[Urmia]] city, mainly in Mergever, Tergever, Dasht, Dashtabel, Roza and Berandez, in Iraqi Kurdistan from [[Mosul]] to [[Hewler]], the capital of the [[Kurdistan Autonomous Region]] and the seat of the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]], and in Turkish Kurdistan around [[Lake Van]] and in the [[Semdinan]] and [[A\u011fr\u0131]] areas.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Kurdish tribes}}\n[[Category:Kurdish tribes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Kurdish tribe}}\n'''Herki''' is the second largest tribe in [[Kurdistan]] after [[Jaff (people)|Jaff]]. The largest part of this tribe live in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] and a significant number live in [[Iranian Kurdistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/harki|title=HARKI \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==Sub-tribes==\nThe Herkis are divided in three sub-tribes: Menda, Sida and Serhati. The Herki dialect belongs to the [[Kurmanji]] dialect.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/13/countries/Turk.html |website=ethnologue.com |publisher=Summer Institute of Linguistics |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Lifestyle==\nThe Herkis lived mostly a [[nomadic]] life with their herds; however, this changed a lot after 1920 and the [[Treaty of S\u00e8vres]]. The new hand-drawn borders of Iran, Iraq, Syria and Turkey hindered [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] tribes to continue their way of life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iraq: Kurdish militia called Harqi (Harki, Herki, Harkki, Harqees) allied; current activities; its relationship with the Iraqi government; tribal affiliations |url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3df4be4c20.html |website=refworld.org |publisher=UNHCR |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>The [[Turkish Gendarmerie]] was famous for its brutality against nomads and their herds. This led to many [[Kurdish tribes]] besides the Herkis leaving their nomadic lifestyle and settled in villages which they had before only used during the winter. The nomadic and free lifestyle they had, was taken from them. \n\nThe new borders soon had a major impact on every aspect of the Kurdish life. For Herkis and many other Kurds that meant that areas which had belonged to them and their herds were taken from them, and they could not move freely like their forefathers had done for a century. They had to decide in which country to settle, which is the reason why Herkis and many other Kurdish tribes can be found dispersed in Iran, Iraq and Turkey, but still be of the same tribe.\n\nIn 1989 they counted some 20,000 people, living between [[Urmia]] and [[Rawanduz]], one if the largest remaining groups of pastoral herders. On their regular movement they brought salt from Iran to Iraq and carried wheat and barley back to Iran.<ref>{{cite book|title=Kurdish Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zc0MAQAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Cultural Survival, Incorporated|pages=34-40}}</ref>\n\nToday, the Herkis live in Iranian Kurdistan around and in [[Urmia]] city, mainly in Mergever, Tergever, Dasht, Dashtabel, Roza and Berandez, in Iraqi Kurdistan from [[Mosul]] to [[Hewler]], the capital of the [[Kurdistan Autonomous Region]] and the seat of the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]], and in Turkish Kurdistan around [[Lake Van]] and in the [[Semdinan]] and [[A\u011fr\u0131]] areas.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Kurdish tribes}}\n[[Category:Kurdish tribes]]\n", "name_user": "Hamza F. G. Harki", "label": "safe", "comment": "included another name that is also widely used.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herki"}
{"title_page": "William Rivers Pitt", "text_new": "'''William Rivers Pitt''' (born November 9, 1971) is an author, editor, and political activist.\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Rivers Pitt was born in [[Washington, D.C.]], and lived several years in [[Alabama]] (where his father, [[Charles Redding Pitt]], later served as [[chairman|chair]] of the state [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]) before eventually moving to [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], where he lived for almost 40 years. He was educated in [[English literature]] at [[College of the Holy Cross|Holy Cross College]], a Catholic college in [[Massachusetts]], and after graduation spent two years in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] doing law-related work.  Upon return to Boston, Pitt taught [[English literature]], [[journalism]], [[grammar]], and [[history]] at a small [[private school]]. In 2002, he joined the staff of the non-profit news organization [[Truthout]] as a contributing writer, and is now lead columnist and a senior editor. He lives and works in [[Keene, New Hampshire]] but remains a devoted [[Sports in Boston|Boston sports]] fan. Pitt is married and has a daughter.\n\n==Writing career==\nPitt became devoted to writing about politics during the [[impeachment]] [[trial (law)|trial]] of former [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]]. Two events -- the disputed [[2000 United States presidential election recount in Florida|2000 election]] followed by the attacks of [[September 11 attacks|September 11]] -- galvanized his activism and his writing, and upon joining the staff at Truthout in 2002 he worked to push back against what he described as \"the rising tide of conservative [[fundamentalism]] in American government\".\n\nPitt's first book, ''War on Iraq: What Team Bush Doesn't Want You to Know'', was published in 2002. It was an in-depth examination of the Bush administration's false WMD arguments set against testimony and data from a weapons ispector who oversaw the destruction of Iraq's stockpiles in the 1990s. In reviewing this book, ''[[The Guardian]]'' called it \"the most comprehensive independent analysis of the state of knowledge about Iraq's weapons programmes until the new team of inspectors went back.\"<ref name=\"gua030125\"/> In December of 2002, the book appeared on the ''New York Times'' best-seller list, was an international best-seller, and was translated into 13 languages. \n\nPitt's second book, ''The Greatest Sedition Is Silence: Four Years in America'',\" was published in 2003. It is an analysis of U.S. politics in areas outside the push for war in Iraq, covering topics such as the Enron collapse, the media and ''Fox News'', but primarily concentrates on the aftermath of the attacks of September 11.\n\nPitt's third book, ''House of Ill Repute: Reflections on War, Lies, and America's Ravaged Reputation,'' was published in 2006. It serves as a second volume to Pitt's first book by compiling the myriad ways the Bush administration lied the U.S. into an invasion of Iraq, and documents the steep cost in blood, treasure and reputation brought by the war. \n\nPitt's fourth book, The Mass Destruction of Iraq: The Disintegration of a Nation: Why It Is Happening, and Who Is Responsible, was published in 2014. The book was co-authored by Truthout reporter Dahr Jamail, who traveled to Iraq after \"Shock and Awe\" and spent months as an unembedded journalist reporting from Fallujah and other hot spots in the war. Pitt and Jamail combined to create a searing indictment of the war, and of those who championed it in Washington D.C. ''Mass Destruction'' is the last volume of Pitt's trilogy on the war.\n\nPitt has covered every presidential and midterm election, and every presidential debate, since 2002.\n\n==Notable Articles 2009-Present==\n\n#[https://truthout.org/articles/please-take-this-because-i-love-you-and-i-might-die-a-covid-tale/ \u201cPlease Take This, Because I Love You and I Might Die\u201d: A COVID Tale], March 30, 2020\n#[https://truthout.org/articles/say-goodbye-to-mitch-mcconnells-america/ Say Goodbye to Mitch McConnell\u2019s America], February 23, 2019\n\n#\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"gua030125\">{{Cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Steele |authorlink=Jonathan Steele |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=A mess of our making |page=11 |date=January 25, 2003 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/iraq.politics |accessdate=March 9, 2010}}</ref>\n<!-- <ref name=\"tru050908\">{{cite web |url=http://archive.truthout.org/article/my-chat-with-will-pitt |publisher=truthout.org |first=Marc |last=Ash |title=My Chat with Will Pitt |date=September 8, 2005}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"truthout_bio\">{{cite web |url=http://truth-out.org/author/itemlist/user/44663 |publisher=truthout.org |title=William Rivers Pitt}}</ref> -->\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pitt, William Rivers}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American online publication editors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Writers from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Writers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n", "text_old": "'''William Rivers Pitt''' (born November 9, 1971) is an author, editor, and political activist.\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Rivers Pitt was born in [[Washington, D.C.]], and lived several years in [[Alabama]] (where his father, [[Charles Redding Pitt]], later served as [[chairman|chair]] of the state [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]) before eventually moving to [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], where he lived for almost 40 years. He was educated in [[English literature]] at [[College of the Holy Cross|Holy Cross College]], a Catholic college in [[Massachusetts]], and after graduation spent two years in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] doing law-related work.  Upon return to Boston, Pitt taught [[English literature]], [[journalism]], [[grammar]], and [[history]] at a small [[private school]]. In 2002, he joined the staff of the non-profit news organization [[Truthout]] as a contributing writer, and is now lead columnist and a senior editor. He lives and works in [[Keene, New Hampshire]] but remains a devoted [[Sports in Boston|Boston sports]] fan. Pitt is married and has a daughter.\n\n==Writing career==\nPitt became devoted to writing about politics during the [[impeachment]] [[trial (law)|trial]] of former [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]]. Two events -- the disputed [[2000 United States presidential election recount in Florida|2000 election]] followed by the attacks of [[September 11 attacks|September 11]] -- galvanized his activism and his writing, and upon joining the staff at Truthout in 2002 he worked to push back against what he described as \"the rising tide of conservative [[fundamentalism]] in American government\".\n\nPitt's first book, ''War on Iraq: What Team Bush Doesn't Want You to Know'', was published in 2002. It was an in-depth examination of the Bush administration's false WMD arguments set against testimony and data from a weapons ispector who oversaw the destruction of Iraq's stockpiles in the 1990s. In reviewing this book, ''[[The Guardian]]'' called it \"the most comprehensive independent analysis of the state of knowledge about Iraq's weapons programmes until the new team of inspectors went back.\"<ref name=\"gua030125\"/> In December of 2002, the book appeared on the ''New York Times'' best-seller list, was an international best-seller, and was translated into 13 languages. \n\nPitt's second book, ''The Greatest Sedition Is Silence: Four Years in America'',\" was published in 2003. It is an analysis of U.S. politics in areas outside the push for war in Iraq, covering topics such as the Enron collapse, the media and ''Fox News'', but primarily concentrates on the aftermath of the attacks of September 11.\n\nPitt's third book, ''House of Ill Repute: Reflections on War, Lies, and America's Ravaged Reputation,'' was published in 2006. It serves as a second volume to Pitt's first book by compiling the myriad ways the Bush administration lied the U.S. into an invasion of Iraq, and documents the steep cost in blood, treasure and reputation brought by the war. \n\nPitt's fourth book, The Mass Destruction of Iraq: The Disintegration of a Nation: Why It Is Happening, and Who Is Responsible, was published in 2014. The book was co-authored by Truthout reporter Dahr Jamail, who traveled to Iraq after \"Shock and Awe\" and spent months as an unembedded journalist reporting from Fallujah and other hot spots in the war. Pitt and Jamail combined to create a searing indictment of the war, and of those who championed it in Washington D.C. ''Mass Destruction'' is the last volume of Pitt's trilogy on the war.\n\nPitt has covered every presidential and midterm election, and every presidential debate, since 2002.\n\n==Notable Articles 2009-Present==\n\n#[https://truthout.org/articles/with-bolton-pompeo-and-trump-in-the-picture-all-bets-are-off-on-iran/ With Bolton, Pompeo and Trump in the Picture, All Bets Are Off on Iran], June 18 2019\n#[https://truthout.org/articles/dont-accept-the-new-normal-keep-outrage-alive/ Don\u2019t Accept the \u201cNew Normal\u201d \u2014 Keep Outrage Alive], June 15 2019\n\n#\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"gua030125\">{{Cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Steele |authorlink=Jonathan Steele |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=A mess of our making |page=11 |date=January 25, 2003 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/iraq.politics |accessdate=March 9, 2010}}</ref>\n<!-- <ref name=\"tru050908\">{{cite web |url=http://archive.truthout.org/article/my-chat-with-will-pitt |publisher=truthout.org |first=Marc |last=Ash |title=My Chat with Will Pitt |date=September 8, 2005}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"truthout_bio\">{{cite web |url=http://truth-out.org/author/i